Please ensure that the class where the code you provide is managed by Spring in a singleton manner

When spring initializes beans, the default is singleton mode, which is only initialized once, but if you do not initialize in singleton mode, it will cause initialization every time you access it.



There are several situations where this result can occur, I will list one first.Refer to the following code：

    public class Index {
        public static void main(String[] args) {
            ApplicationContext AcContext = new AnnotationConfigApplicationContext(MyConfigration.class);
    
            C1 C1_1 = AcContext.getBean(&quot;c1&quot;, C1.class);
